{{Cleanup FJC Bio}}
'''Hiram Hamilton Ward''' (April 29, 1923 &ndash; April 4, 2002) was a [[United States federal judge]].

Ward was born in [[Thomasville, North Carolina]]. He received a [[LL.B.]] from [[Wake Forest University School of Law]] in 1950. He was in the [[United States Army]] Air Force Lieutenant Colonel from 1940 to 1945. He was in private practice of law in [[Denton, North Carolina]] from 1950 to 1951. He was a Staff attorney of National Production Authority, Washington, DC from 1951 to 1952. He was in private practice of law in [[Lexington and Denton, North Carolina]] from 1952 to 1972. He was an Interim judge, Recorder's Court, Denton, North Carolina in 1961. 

Ward was a federal judge to the [[United States District Court for the Middle District of North Carolina]]. Ward was nominated by President [[Richard M. Nixon]] on May 18, 1972, to a seat vacated by [[Edwin M. Stanley]]. He was confirmed by the [[United States Senate]] on June 28, 1972, and received commission the same day. Served as chief judge, 1982-1988. Assumed [[senior status]] on August 20, 1988. Ward<!-- -->'s service was terminated on April 4, 2002, due to death.

He died in [[Winston-Salem, North Carolina]].

